Every call I had with her was pleasant and she was always very helpful doing all that she could to accommodate. When I was there, she made me feel comfortable engaging in conversation. Paul was my estimator and he was also phenomenal. He had someone rush across town to pickup a part for my vehicle that morning for pickup so that my car will be ready on time. He also had my messy car cleaned and vacuumed. The car looked so good at pickup, especially my bumper. I was so impressed with the outcome I couldn't stop smiling and telling them how happy I was. The whole process was very smooth which was a huge surprise to me. I started out extremely upset due to someone hitting my front bumper and taking off. However everything was as smooth as it can get. I was worried I would have to find someone to go with me for pickup and drop-off but nope, the rental car was at Certified Collison Center waiting for me and I was able to drop it off there too. I can't thank Paul, Taylor and my AAA adjuster Laila Morris enough. You guys are amazing. Hero's in my eyes... Take care all, especially during this COVID-19 Pandemic. <review>When my car was actually, finally ready, after delays and making me come in when it was half done, the workmanship was good.
But the experience before completion and after pickup was not what I expect to from a business.
I dropped off my vehicle as instructed and when instructed. I'm told to expect it that Friday. Friday comes, they tell me that the guy that disassembled it no longer works there, that it might take the guy stepping in to assemble it a little longer, since he didn't take it apart. I was told it might be ready end of day Friday, if not, Monday late morning, since they need to do a quality assurance check once done
Monday morning I'm told it will be ready Monday afternoon. Monday afternoon I'm told it will be ready Tuesday morning. Tuesday morning I'm told it will be ready Tuesday afternoon. Tuesday afternoon they tell me they really don't know when it will be done since they are backlogged with the guy leaving and no one there was sure how my bumper goes on. So I insisted they provide a rental car, which they did, my insurance stopped paying on Monday since the shop told my insurance it would be ready.
Wednesday the shop calls to say my car is done. Funny how fast they move when it's costing them money. I make the trip up there and they bring out my car. They did replace the bumper and paint a body panel, but two other damaged pieces of trim weren't changed and these were on the estimate. I guess quality assurance doesn't check things very closely. To make it worse, they don't know where my parts are. The guy that quit must have them I was told. They overnighted new ones and it was ready the next day. They tell me to leave the rental with them. They did pay the rental, but I got stuck with a gas bill from the rental company. I think the shop should've stepped and paid that. It was their fault my car took an extra week.<//review>< Pics>

<username>Connor Moore<//username><Rating>5<//Rating>< date>
1585862603266<//date>
< Text>
This is my favorite coffee shop period. The owners are incredibly knowledgable and excited about coffee. They go out of their way to learn your name and make you feel like this really is your roastery!

They roast all their own beans, and source from a variety of locations. The pour over Geisha coffee from Panama was the best I've had in my life. There is a free pour over with every bag of beans, so you can compare how your brew tastes against their masterful brew! It's incredible when Christine brews the coffee it tastes like premium coffee flavored tea, it's so smooth and perfectly extracted!< /Text>

<GmapID>0x80857ff1f05faac5:0x91f6acb58b4a0d3e</GmapID><rating>5< /rating><resp>None< /resp>< user_name>
Andrew Tom< /user_name>
<review>Tucked along the busy MLK thoroughfare, two coffee aficionados share their labor of love.  I walked in to Christine (the barista) serving a latte topped with a two-colored heart-within-a-heart, delivered with a wholesome, "thank you for your support!"  As humble newcomers to the specialty coffee scene in Berkeley, their commitment to mastering their craft is authentic and what will certainly sets their shop apart.

What made me excited to visit them was how they've staked their reputation on roasting their own beans.  Most small cafes will launch by brewing and serving the beans of reputable roasters, but Peter and Christine are drawing from their years of experience to roast and serve delicate cups of coffee in a cafe of their own design.

"It's like walking through a time machine," said Peter in describing his thoughts behind building the countertops. "[As you walk in] it's modern, but stepping into the back it becomes more historic."

I ordered a washed Ethiopia pour over coffee, and watched our artist at work. Christine's pour over technique was wonderful - delivering a floral coffee with a sweet lingering aftertaste.  She explained her coffee with the excitement of a musician telling the story behind a new piece: quick to point out how the coffee she made, with beans aged 20 days past roasting, had a gentler taste than when it was first roasted.

MY Coffee Roastery is elevating the specialty coffee scene here in the East Bay, and they're doing so in the most authentic way possible: by studying every roast, educating the community around their coffee, and making people happy with every cup they serve.< /review><pictures>None< /pictures>< Date>
1565028729426</Date>

<name>isabel hsiao<//name><Resp>{'time': 1496544256994, 'text': 'Hi Isabel,\nThank you very much for taking the time to write a review for us. However, in order for us to give out the certificate of completion, the law requires driving schools to issue the certificate only after completing the required 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training, not after the 2nd lesson.\n\nWe strongly encourage students or parents to please email or call to make appointments for all 3 of their 2 hour lessons. Normally we provide some advanced techniques ("Do\'s and Dont\'s") to help students pass the DMV test in all lessons, and especially in the third lesson, which is typically taken just prior to the DMV test appointment. But during the driving lessons, we observe the student\'s progress and capability to drive before we start to have them use these advanced level skills which they may not be comfortable with.\n\nWe apologize for any inconvenience, but our number one priority is always the student\'s safety. We would be happy to help you finish your final class so we can complete your preparation for your driving test.'}<//Resp>< Time>

<Gmap_id>0x80dccd2af804e461:0x475055e74c65b4e2<//Gmap_id><Text>Second only to making my own beer at home, trying good beer and drinking at good craft breweries is pretty much my favorite thing in life. I try not to be snobby about it but I take my beer seriously. Personally, I would rate I&I brewing as the best craft brewery in the Inland Empire area of Southern California.
Their beers are divers and unique. No matter if you like big bold flavored beers or lighter more refreshing less ‚Äúaggressive‚Äù beers, you will be able to find something that you like.
The staff is always helpful with directing customers towards a beer that suits their individual pallet. The brewer is incredibly talented at blending stiles and specialty ingredients. I have never been disappointed by a beer at I&I and there is a new beer on tap almost every time I go there.
The location is a small out of the way place and the atmosphere is super casual. You can sit at a counter out in the brewery, have conversations and enjoy your beer.
Perhaps not everyone agrees with me but I highly recommend giving I&I a try. Especially if you enjoy trying something unique and delicious that you probably can‚Äôt get anywhere ells.</Text><user>101438726369844595878< /user>< Pics>

<Rate>3<//Rate><Text>After tasting several of their beers at beer festivals, I finally visited I&I. I stopped by on a Friday night close to last call (9pm) and the place was pretty packed. They have a small tasting room, so if you plan on visiting with a big group, be sure to get there early and claim your spot. As for the beers, I would say half of those on tap were good, while the others seemed to be more of an after thought. The tap list seemed to be cut short, so there may be more than the 15 beers (good offering) available on tap when I stopped by. < Review>
They have 20 beers on tap and give you tasters!

I had the pastrami sandwich and it was delicious.  They put coleslaw on the sandwich, which sounded weird, but it was a great complementary flavor.  It came with giant potato chips that were fresh, beautifully crispy, and tasty.  I think they'd just been fried.

Service was very prompt and attentive when needed.  Michael checked to make sure everything was OK and came when we were done to see if we wanted/needed anything else, which shows he kept a surreptitious eye on us.

So...delicious food and prompt service!< /Review>

<Text>We came out see our friend Bill perform with his band.  First time to this wine bar, they are in the midst of changing ownership so seems a bit understaffed.  However, service was courteous and friendly.

It was a nice group of us coming to see Bill.  Music was awesome, by the way.  We got lucky and sat at the last seats available at the bar.  Definitely my preferred seating location.  Good view of the musicians. Good accessibility to the bartenders too!

We had a few glasses of wine each.  Ordered the saut√©ed mushrooms and toasted baguette, but that night they served with pita bread which was good anyway.

Also ordered the coconut shrimp with sweet and sour sauce.  Tasty.

Probably should have ordered like a burger or something, because I definitely drank more than I ate.  (Yes, we did take lyft here!  Don't drink and drive!!)

<Rating>4< /Rating><Text>Excellent service!  Wonderful wines!  We enjoyed the wine tasting and the sommelier was helpful, and fun....but the reason it's getting four and not five stars is the cheese plate.  Ugh....the cheese plate, if you're serving wine and offer a cheese plate, please make the effort.  The "candied nuts" should be added to the plate when serving, not on the previously prepared plate that is sitting in the refrigerator, they get soggy.  The dried fruits should also be added when you're ready to serve so you can actually bite them without breaking teeth. < text>
This place seems to be hit or miss. I enjoyed my burger but the other burger at the table was overdone. The chips they come with were tasteless and greasy. Pastrami sandwich was good but the tomato bisque was spicy for some reason?? Chicken strips were overcooked and mostly breading but the garlic fries were amazing. They also ran out of several menu items and we were there before the lunch rush.
Server was very friendly but service itself was slow. Entrees all came out at different times (even the burgers which youd think would be cooked simultaneously). Took forever to get the check. And with how little seating is inside you'd think theyd want to move people as quickly as possible to make room for the next guests.</text>

< Review>
I attended a Mother's Day plant night at Brix. Although I enjoyed the company and I enjoyed the project that we made at the plant night. I was not impressed by the service or the food. The service by the one gentleman that seem to be waiting on our entire area was good. He was as efficient as could be expected. But I just feel that they were understaffed for the amount of people that were in attendance. I had chicken strips and they were not good and one of my big gripes about restaurants that sell chicken strips is how stingy they are with the ranch dressing! If you spend $13 for chicken strips you could expect to get a little more than a half a cup of ranch dressing that's as thin as water. I personally appreciate the people that I was with and the project, but again I was unimpressed with Brix and have no intention of returning there. However, my brother dies live 2 blocks ( walking distance) from Brix... If He suggests going there sometime, I just may give it another try. But that's only if my brother suggests it!<//Review>

< Text>
MG Club of So Cal stopped by to eat after one of our outings. i didn't know what to expect but found the surrounding inviting and homey. I called right away to schedule an appointment for Saturday morning and I explained that Honda America acknowledged this defect and the dealership will treat this as such. Make sure you ask for that info as soon as you sit down with financing!

< text>
Over the last few years I have had my share of bs car dealerships and shady sales people. So much that when I first contacted Pacific Honda I was already on the defensive side. I emailed an inquiry regarding a Honda accord. A sales person by the name of Joji replied to my inquiry on May 4th. He asked if he could call me. I said no, that I want to communicate through email only. ( I do this so I can reference back just in case . ) Joji respected my wishes and by May 6th we had over 30 emails going back and forth. Never once did he talk about prices ,credit scores, or push for me to come in.
One day I emailed him and his boss called me and told me Joji was off that day and he would get back to me. He didn't try to get involved or push a sale, simply a courtesy call. Later that day Joji actually replied back to my email and answered more of my questions. ON HIS DAY OFF! I thought that was pretty cool. We continued to talk and he respectfully answered all my questions,never once pushing for a sale. He told me at the beginning, when your ready then we will talk  and he kept his word. Then on May 8th I emailed him and asked if I could come and look at some cars. He said yes and I came in on May 9th.  Prior to coming in, I told Joji, do not hand me off to someone else when I get there and I'm only looking and can not buy right now. He said no problem.
May 9th I come in and he shows me three different cars lets me test drive one. The whole time nothing was mentioned about buying a car. When I was done test driving  the car. I told him I liked it and yes I ended up getting it. Lol but Joji and pacific Honda let me make that choice. They handled all my objections to buying a car earlier that I wanted. Meaning : worked with me on my down payment and delayed my first car payment, so I would have time to return my lemon car Im currently in.  The best part! They gave me the car payment I wanted, well 3 cents over but come on! 3 cents. Lol
Bottom line Joji was an excellent person to work with. Seriously.. I felt relaxed and most important safe when doing business with him.
Thank you Joji. Thank you Pacific Honda. Way to leave a good 1st impression!
PS We all know dealerships are your best friends until you sign the paperwork and drive off with your new car, then they pretty much wash there hand of you. Honestly though My gut didn't feel that way with Joji or the dealership itself. I hope my gut it right. If not I will definitely update! :)< /text>

I arrived at Pacific Honda about 9:00 a.m., June 16th.  As soon as I pulled in a screener asked me what type of service I needed.  I told him just a scheduled maintenance according to the manual. < review>
Pacific Honda failed to satisfy our purchase experience at every turn. After letting the salesperson know that we had to leave by 6pm at 4pm (after arriving at 2pm for our scheduled appointment), we still did not complete the purchase. That was fine as Pacific Honda needed to complete recall repairs before releasing the vehicle. We completed the vast majority of paperwork and they promised the vehicle would be available the next day (Saturday) and they would call us when it was ready.

Saturday came and along about 2pm and I had not heard from them, so I called. It turns out they don't do recall repairs on the weekend, so the car wouldn't be available till Monday.

Monday comes and I receive a call from the dealership saying the car was "ready for pickup". It was about noon, so I went down during my lunch break. This was nothing but failure. They made my wife and I wait for 30 mins before talking to a person. The car WAS NOT READY. Despite a call to the contrary, they had not completed all work necessary to release the vehicle. The sales manager then had the gall to lay the blame on us when the message on my voicemail clearly said "Your car is ready for pickup." Finally, they lost our paperwork. So a trip that should have been 15 mins took 2 hours.

We then had to return for a 3rd time later in the week as they had forgotten to give us the 2nd key and the users manual. We were told upon going out of our way to pick up those items that it was our fault they had been forgotten because WE were in a rush to get out of there previously.

We were also promised that we would receive standard review of features in the car and that they would be contacting us to schedule this. It has been weeks now and we have not heard a word from Honda about this. We were specifically asked to mark on our survey that this review had been completed despite it not.

I would have given Pacific Honda one star, but the sales person Ryan was pleasant and informative. Every other part of the experience failed to meet expectations.</review>

< Text>
My 11 year old Honda Civic EX 2010 needed some significant work this time. The Low Tire Pressure Indicator always comes on while driving. Plus, the car was leaking oil on garage floor.

Yesterday 06/25/20. I called about getting my car inspected. I met advisor Jun Iwasaki . His mechanic diagnosed the problem and Jun suggested my car needed to change a new oil filter.

7:15 am waited for fixing the oil change. Around 9 am, I received  a follow up call informing me all work was complete. I picked up my car and checked the low tire pressure light was gone. Also, no more oil leaking problems.

<Text>I and my wife are writing this feedback based on our experience with Honda Pacific, which has been difficult.

- We decided to lease a car and signed our contract with Pacific Honda, San Diego CA on October 27, 2019. We wanted to make our first brand new car lease or purchase from an experienced store so we could be guided through the process. After signing the contract, we brought our student IDs in order to benefit a $500 student discount and it was when the representative realized our visa type and said he should show it to the manager.
- It was understandable that the young representative was not familiar with the student visa, even though we informed that we are international, doing our masters and working at the same time before we signed the contract. After weeks of stressful waiting without knowing if the car was taken back or not, finally, we were told that we weren‚Äôt suitable for a leasing contract but we could buy the car.
- We agreed to buy the car, paid the $1000 difference (between leasing and purchase) on down payment and signed a new contract. We made this payment with our credit card in the Pacific Honda store with a Finance department representative. A week later, they told us we should have made the payment from a debit card instead of a credit card. We told that we already paid our credit card bill for that month and they asked for the statement, which we provided later.
- We couldn‚Äôt understand why our payment method was incorrect considering we made the payment with the finance department and they approved the credit card. However, we were fine because finally it was solved after we provided the statement and they approved. The following week, we realized our $1000 payment was refunded to our account with no explanation and we were back to where we started.
- Imagine, a customer wants to make a payment but the seller keeps making it hard. After weeks of trying hard, we finally could make the down payment and waited until January 8, when was the due date for the first payment to the bank. But, we weren‚Äôt informed about how we could make the payment because Pacific Honda was in communication with Capital One. When we called to have information about the payment process, we learned that Pacific Honda didn‚Äôt send the deal to Capital One on time, so the offer had expired.
- As we mentioned above, we specifically chose Pacific Honda based on their experience because we needed assistance through the process as a first-time purchaser. We believe, all the misfortune we had was based on a lack of knowledge or communication between the departments. Information given or action taken by a department was rejected by another department while we were never informed properly about what was the next. When we wanted to return the car, they said we cannot give it back but Honda can take it back if necessary. The amount of stress and unknown we had made us regret this purchase. Almost after 3 months, we could finalize the process by making the first payment in January and decided to write this feedback.
- We understand problems may occur during a sales process, which is okay. What we care is the way it‚Äôs handled and if the company is solution-oriented. Unfortunately, we couldn‚Äôt see this effort and the lack of communication within the company caused us a lot of time and stress. We are writing this feedback by hoping no one else has the same experience we had.

Regards,
Okan & Begum AKDAG< /Text>< Pictures>

<name>Cory Lyle< /name>< Review>
This was my second experience with Pacific Honda.  Three years ago I leased a new Honda Fit through them and had a fantastic experience from the moment I walked through the door. Mark took great care of me and walked me through all of the steps until I was out the door and driving home in my new car.

Well...fast forward three years and it is time to upgrade to a bigger car to accommodate my growing family.  Again, I was taken care of by Mark, but this time I was purchasing a new CR-V EX.  Mark was very transparent through the process and had the car in pristine condition.  He walked me through all the new safety features and technology included in the EX model.   It felt pretty good to drive off in a fresh new car knowing that I got a great deal.

I don't normally go to the dealership for my problems but I am so glad I did. I was so impressed by their flexibility, consumer service, honesty and accommodations. Originally, I called for an appointment a few days before the new year (a very busy time of year for them). They had no appointments for the entire week but the woman on the phone promised to get me in if I came in when they opened at 7AM. When I arrived the next day, I walked inside and waited maybe 2-3 minutes. Brandon greeted me and asked what the problem was. I was in to my check engine light. He told me it was most likely my Hybrid battery and that it would be FULLY COVERED by the warranty because it was less than 11 years old and under 170,000 miles. I left my car there and a few hours later Brandon called and told me the good news. He also let me know that my car would be ready around 3-4PM the next day but, he wouldn't be here so his associate Tony would be taking care of me. The next day at 9AM, Tony called me and let me know my car was ready. My experience was fast, easy and didn't cost me a cent. That deserves 5 stars.</text>

< review>
I and my wife are writing this feedback based on our experience with Honda Pacific, which has been difficult.

- We decided to lease a car and signed our contract with Pacific Honda, San Diego CA on October 27, 2019. We wanted to make our first brand new car lease or purchase from an experienced store so we could be guided through the process. After signing the contract, we brought our student IDs in order to benefit a $500 student discount and it was when the representative realized our visa type and said he should show it to the manager.
- It was understandable that the young representative was not familiar with the student visa, even though we informed that we are international, doing our masters and working at the same time before we signed the contract. After weeks of stressful waiting without knowing if the car was taken back or not, finally, we were told that we weren‚Äôt suitable for a leasing contract but we could buy the car.
- We agreed to buy the car, paid the $1000 difference (between leasing and purchase) on down payment and signed a new contract. We made this payment with our credit card in the Pacific Honda store with a Finance department representative. A week later, they told us we should have made the payment from a debit card instead of a credit card. We told that we already paid our credit card bill for that month and they asked for the statement, which we provided later.
- We couldn‚Äôt understand why our payment method was incorrect considering we made the payment with the finance department and they approved the credit card. However, we were fine because finally it was solved after we provided the statement and they approved. The following week, we realized our $1000 payment was refunded to our account with no explanation and we were back to where we started.
- Imagine, a customer wants to make a payment but the seller keeps making it hard. After weeks of trying hard, we finally could make the down payment and waited until January 8, when was the due date for the first payment to the bank. But, we weren‚Äôt informed about how we could make the payment because Pacific Honda was in communication with Capital One. When we called to have information about the payment process, we learned that Pacific Honda didn‚Äôt send the deal to Capital One on time, so the offer had expired.
- As we mentioned above, we specifically chose Pacific Honda based on their experience because we needed assistance through the process as a first-time purchaser. We believe, all the misfortune we had was based on a lack of knowledge or communication between the departments. Information given or action taken by a department was rejected by another department while we were never informed properly about what was the next. When we wanted to return the car, they said we cannot give it back but Honda can take it back if necessary. The amount of stress and unknown we had made us regret this purchase. Almost after 3 months, we could finalize the process by making the first payment in January and decided to write this feedback.
- We understand problems may occur during a sales process, which is okay. What we care is the way it‚Äôs handled and if the company is solution-oriented. Unfortunately, we couldn‚Äôt see this effort and the lack of communication within the company caused us a lot of time and stress. We are writing this feedback by hoping no one else has the same experience we had.

Regards,
Okan & Begum AKDAG< /review>

<Time>1579645697574</Time><rate>2</rate><review>UPDATE: As of 01/21/20 I still have not heard back from anyone at Pacific Honda regarding either of my issues. Someone left a message below, saying to contact them, but left no name. When I call the number I get passed around and eventually leave messages for sales managers who have not called me back.

I recently purchased a pre-owned vehicle at Pacific Honda in San Diego. My salesperson, Greg, was excellent. Very accommodating with test drives, vehicle checks, etc. He was not high pressure, so I felt very comfortable with him. Everyone at the facility seemed very nice. So far, I am mostly quite happy with the vehicle, and felt I got it for a decent price.

There are just two reasons I am giving a 3 instead of 4 or 5 stars:

1. There was/is a problem with one of the electric windows. I realize I purchased the vehicle "as is"; but I discovered this problem about 2 days after I brought the vehicle home. I contacted Greg via email, and also mentioned it to a representative (whose name I cannot remember) who had called me a few days later to check in on my experience. No one ever got back to me or offered to look at the window to fix it. It is still a problem, and I can tell it's something electrical with the driver's side control, because from the passenger side it opens and closes fine. But again, I never got a response from Pacific Honda regarding this issue. Sort of makes me feel that once the transaction is done, they are done with you.

2. I just recently received a notice in the mail that they ran a credit check/report on me. I paid CASH for this car; so there was absolutely no reason to run my credit. It's no big deal, but it just shouldn't be done. Depending on who you talk to this activity can lower your score. I know of no benefit Pacific Honda would gain from doing this; but who knows? All I know is that they did run an unauthorized credit check. I called the number on the notification letter who said they would pass a message on to the dealership. I want to request they take that activity off my credit history. I have never heard back from anyone at Pacific Honda.

They have a good selection of new and used cars. And again, Greg was great and they were all very nice. However, because of the two issues above, I am doubtful I would go back to them or recommend them.

< Review>
The people who helped me out, individually, were each amazing (Samantha H, Dario, and Scott, specifically, but I also dealt with other employees as well). Scott helped me with finding the right car for me, and went over the features of the cars and how they fit me. Dario helped me with getting my credit approved, which wasn't easy, given what my credit is. Samantha went over the paperwork with me, and made sure I understood all the options I had for the car and all the other details (security features, what happens at the end of my lease, etc).

However, the most frustrating part about my experience was the poor communication, or lack thereof. I had to give my information (address, contact info, income, references) multiple times to different people. After about 4 times giving my info, Dario finally managed to get a deal that I could agree to. Additionally, after I was approved, I received little instruction on what to do next. I was not told what information I would need to bring in, which led to a last minute scramble to find it all in time (which I still didn't).

Despite these frustrating periods, my overall experience was positive. I got a great car that I love for a payment that's good for me. Now I guess I just need to wait until I need service on the car to see how that branch of Pacific Honda handles.</Review>

<Name>Bob Chambers<//Name><Time>1391456836249<//Time><rating>2<//rating>< text>
I bought a new car here -- 2013 Accord Coupe -- I feel that I got a good deal because it was one of the last 2013s on the lot.

Pros:

--My salesman Scott was very nice and not too high pressure.
--There was a small scratch on the back bumper. They took care of it (I think maybe they repainted the bumper) and even put me in a rental car overnight for free.
--The service advisor was very pleasant to deal with.

Cons:

--My biggest problem was dealing with the F&I (Finance and Insurance) person. There was a very high-pressure pitch to buy:
--extended warranty (she made it sound like my Accord would blow up the day after the factory warranty expired...I didn't know that Honda made such junky cars)
--maintenance plan
--door ding plan (no kidding)
--Lo-Jack
--window VIN etching

Even though I said "no" several times, the pressure continued throughout the pitch. It was not a pleasant experience.

--As I mentioned, they needed to keep the car overnight, and gave me a free rental, which was nice, but when I picked it up the next morning it was covered with water drops from being outside overnight. I had just washed and waxed the car and was not happy about this.

An observation, not sure if it's a pro or con:
--The service department was very, very busy when I only the car there to get the bumper scratch repaired. Although they seemed pretty efficient, I would have a little concern about getting work done there on a regular basis. Maybe they're busy because they're good, or it could be that they have a central location in San Diego.<//text>

< Review>
Although I did not buy my car from Pacific Honda, I wanted to leave a review to help other buyers.

Pacific Honda offered a pretty good "E-price" over email. I will admit it was hard to beat. I waited a few more days and contacted more dealerships and got it for a few hundred less because I was not in a rush.

I think overall Pacific Honda is alittle bit more straightforward. They can offer you OTD prices quick so you know exactly where you stand.

I rated most of the dealerships I shopped at. Look around and be patient to find the best price. Always do your research!</Review>

< review>
I had been thinking about a buying a car for some time, but I tend to procrastinate.  I searched the internet, and decided on a Honda Civic.  I was visiting my son in San Diego, and we decided to just go out to look, and maybe test drive a Civic sedan.  When we got to Honda Pacific, which my son chose because of its excellent reviews, we were greeted by Angelina James.  I told her exactly what I was looking for, down to the color, and she asked us to give her a minute.  Almost immediately, she drove the exact car I mentioned, to where we were standing. I decided to test drive the car. It was everything I wanted, but I still wasn't sure I wanted to buy the car that day. Angelina was very professional, not pushy, and explained everything.  She was very personable, and easy to talk with.  I ultimately decided to buy the car.  After all of the paperwork was completed, Angelina spent a long time helping me to understand the phone, navigation system, and other parts of the car.  She acted like she valued me as a customer, even after the car was signed, sealed and delivered.  She did a follow-up call to see how I liked the car, and to thank me for buying it.  I had a very pleasant experience, which was much shorter that I anticipated - from start to finish. I highly recommend Angelina James, and if I were to give her a grade it would be an A+. I would not hesitate to send a friend to Pacific Honda, and I would recommend that they ask for Angelina James.<//review>

I went pacific Honda over the weekend because my check engine light was on. When I got there, their express service had a 2.5 hr line. A week ago my wonderful father checked the tire pressure in my car. He confused my car with my sisters and thought my tires had too much air in them so he let some air out of each. As i pulled away, the "tire pressure" notification came on. So I pulled over, checked the tire pressure of each with my tire gauge and realized what had happened. I had the irritating tire pressure notification in my car for a week and I couldn't for the life of me figure out how to make it go away. I read the manual and was just struggling. So I thought "I'll just pop into the Honda store and ask someone to guide me." When I arrived, a guy walked up to me and asked me the problem. He told me there was "no way to change the notification" and that I had to get my car inspected. I understand the liability of Honda's to need to check each of my tires before I leave the service lot (obviously.) But he continued to repeat "I'm sure the real problem is that the tires really don't have the accurate amount of air in them" insinuating that I really don't know how to check my own tires. Mind you, I'm a 25-year-old female and I get the "pity" and "incompetent" look from people like him often. I did some more research and I was able to google a resolution. Low and behold, the notification went away in just a few moments.

< Review>
I went pacific Honda over the weekend because my check engine light was on. When I got there, their express service had a 2.5 hr line. Fair enough, they have no control over how busy they get, although they could have set up an appointment process. I went to the regular service counter after that and asked what the code in my car meant, and they said that it was the 60K service and that to do that it would cost me $495, I mentioned that I had done my 30K in Oregon and that I don't seem to recall it having cost that much money. They claimed differences in markets, cost of living, etc.

I called my Oregon Honda dealership, and they said that the 60K service cost was $189. I can understand cost of living differences, but $450 vs $189???? really?? so I then decided to call a few other dealers around California, and another one in San Diego charges $270, so I went back in to talk to the service manager and asked why the difference. His answer "I don't know what to tell you!"

I have always had a great experience with Honda dealerships until I got to this one. I'm not exactly sure how Honda Corporation allows this to happen, but they have lost me as a costumer, and I hope they lose many other customers they are trying to cheat out of their rightfully earned money.</Review>

<Rate>1</Rate>< Text>
I bought a 2015 Honda civic from Pacific Honda in June, 2018. This week when I went to the Pacific Honda Service for a reset in tire pressure checking system, a service guy told me that one of my tire is in different brand with the other three tires. That one is from Yokohama, and the other three are from Michelin, which is the original tire model. I was shocked that this could happen on a car bought from a serious dealership, not from a random guy trying to rip me off. The mismatch in tires is definitely causing different handling in tires due to the material, construction and tread design from different tire manufactuers, and therefore leading to long-term issues in car, such as alignment, suspension and transmission problems.

I went to the Pacific Honda to talk about this and asked for a replacement of the mismatched pair of tires, or at least that one Yokohama tire. The manager, Jose Rogrigues, was trying to convince me that the two mismatched tire are exactly the same without even going out to have a look at my car. He offers to cover only half of the price to replace the Yokohama tire, since it is "not a safety-related issue". How come they can define this is not related to safety? The car parts related to tires could fail earlier than they are supposed to be. When I bought the car, I was told all the tires are new, so I didn't ask if the tires are matched. Aren't the tires supposed to be MATCHED on a car? Another manager, Curtis Ringle, performed a "I have asked my boss and this is the best we can do" act. This is really annoying and disappointing. I am writing this down to let people know never go to Pacific Honda for used car shopping. They will only treat you well before you buy a car from them.</Text>

<rating>1< /rating>< review>
I bought a 2015 Honda civic from Pacific Honda in June, 2018. This week when I went to the Pacific Honda Service for a reset in tire pressure checking system, a service guy told me that one of my tire is in different brand with the other three tires. That one is from Yokohama, and the other three are from Michelin, which is the original tire model. I was shocked that this could happen on a car bought from a serious dealership, not from a random guy trying to rip me off. The mismatch in tires is definitely causing different handling in tires due to the material, construction and tread design from different tire manufactuers, and therefore leading to long-term issues in car, such as alignment, suspension and transmission problems.

I went to the Pacific Honda to talk about this and asked for a replacement of the mismatched pair of tires, or at least that one Yokohama tire. The manager, Jose Rogrigues, was trying to convince me that the two mismatched tire are exactly the same without even going out to have a look at my car. He offers to cover only half of the price to replace the Yokohama tire, since it is "not a safety-related issue". How come they can define this is not related to safety? The car parts related to tires could fail earlier than they are supposed to be. When I bought the car, I was told all the tires are new, so I didn't ask if the tires are matched. Aren't the tires supposed to be MATCHED on a car? Another manager, Curtis Ringle, performed a "I have asked my boss and this is the best we can do" act. This is really annoying and disappointing. I am writing this down to let people know never go to Pacific Honda for used car shopping. They will only treat you well before you buy a car from them.<//review>

< Review>
I have to admit that I get a stomach ache when I usually walk onto a car dealership lot. I love cars.  I used to go with my dad and test drive cars for fun as a kid, but I get uncomfortable with the high-pressure sales the usually comes with walking onto a dealer lot.  Pacific Honda was a completely different, and wonderfully refreshing experience.  I don't do a lot of online reviews, but after reading a previous scathing review, I feel like I need to tell my wonderfully positive experience.  I'm also going to post this on yelp.  This place deserves some kudos and cookies.  I had a pretty good idea what kind of car and model I wanted, the Pilot Touring.  Marcos was informative, friendly, and helpful.  I NEVER felt pressured.  When it came time to talk about price, he and Paul (the sales manager) were open and fair.  Paul was clear about what he had available, what discounts he could give (and couldn't) and what he was willing to do. I'd done my research, so I knew what I could afford and what was a fair price.  I hate haggling, back-n-forth negotiation stuff.  I want to treat people with respect and fairness and I want to be treated the same.   We agreed on a fair price, a great price.  I don't make purchases like this without talking it over with my wife (duh!).  They never flinched when I told them I would talk about it that night and call them in the morning. I'd been to 3 other dealerships (Toyota and Honda) and ALWAYS got pressured to make a purchase that day.  Paul encouraged me to make the best decision for me and my family.  When I went back the next day, Paul and Tony were great. (Marcos was out, but he connected us with Tony who answered every question.)  It was the Dec 31st, so Paul was slammed with everybody else trying to get a purchase done before the end of the year stuff, but he STILL made the effort to come talk to us 3-4 times and check in.  I know they are trying to sell cars, but he could have sat in his office. Instead, he took a moment to make sure that we were happy.  My parents purchased a CRV from Pacific Honda, and we got the Pilot we wanted for a price I would have had to fight to get at another dealership. I walked out feeling positive, happy, and relaxed (not pressured and defensive like other dealerships).  I would HIGHLY recommend you go and talk to them if you are in the market for a new car.< /Review>

<Review>Came to Pacific Honda to buy a brand new car for my mom and was greeted as soon as we pulled up by Jon our salesman. He instantly put us at ease and we did not feel pressured at all to buy a car. Jon was very straightforward, helpful, and came of fas sincere in trying to help my mom find a car that she really liked. After a couple of test drives, my mom settled on a 2012 brownish/grey Honda Civic. The easy part was finding the car, now the real fun begins.

Being in auto finance has given me an inside perspective on buying a car. Never settle for the MSRP price on a new car and if you aren't at some point getting up out of your seat to walk out of the dealership then you haven't negotiated hard enough.

Well, I was pleasantly surprised with how things worked out. Jon gave me the invoice price of the vehicle and even worked out a deal for us on the alarm. Although the interest rate was unappealing at first, Jon was able to work with the finance manager to get the rate adjusted and an even further price discount on the car! Amazing! I didn't think it was possible for me to feel so at ease, but Jon made every effort to make this transaction pleasant!

My mom is happy with her new car, the financing, and the way we were treated by Jon at this dealership. As long as Pacific Honda has Jon as a salesman, we will back again for the 2013 Honda Accord when I am ready to buy!

Thank you Jon and Pacific Honda!< /Review></record>

<review>What ever happened to customer service? Let me make sure when you read this review you will understand why I'm frustrated and disappointed. The whole experience could have been fantastic review. Here's why...
My Partner and I bought a 2012 Honda Civic LX brand new. Upon getting financed we already knew our finance rate was going to be higher than previously purchased Honda's from the same dealership because of some financial setbacks from 2 years prior. He had to get a car for work reasons and we didn't want some other used car with problems from a previous owner. So the sales person gave us a 17% interest rate which was not negotiable. Again it is what it is. It didn't matter we had bought 2 other brand new Honda's from Pacific Honda. They put my name as the buyer his name as the co-maker. We caught that and that was supposed to have been changed. We got every excuse from it was the bank who did that to they lost the paperwork and so on. Finally after 8 months it appears the names are corrected. He is the legal owner and I the co-signer. Now normally a co-signer does not get monthly bills unless there is a problem with the owner. Up until the last 4-6 months I have received a monthly bill and he sometimes never got one.
He has been paying 17% interest and still is and the dealership has gotten a kick back from Chase Bank for bringing us the customer to them. The amount that gets applied to the principle each month ranges from $175-$200. Our car payment is $423.00 per month. The bank and the dealership are getting more than $225 per month in interest. Now we've all heard of being ripped off but this is what I call getting the screws put to you with a smile. Any reputable business that is truly into customer service and would like a customer to be happy wouldn't do this. We knew the interest was going to be higher before going the Honda dealership but not that high. Pacific Honda is not a buy here pay here tiny dealership or car lot, they are one of the biggest Honda dealerships on the West Coast part of another parent company even larger.
So I would be very careful about buying your next car from this dealership. There has been many times we had little to eat because of struggling to pay them and all the other bills that you have in life.
The service department never answers their phone it's all voicemail. You sit on hold and then get transferred to reservations just to book service. The service advisors will not call you back and more than not the items needed fixed on the car are never done the same day because they need more time. Now remember he dropped his car off at 8-9am they have it all day, he gets a rental pays for the rental and then at 6pm comes back thinking the repairs are going to be done and they aren't. They tell you when you leave the car that they will have everything repaired when you leave it, then it's we got too busy and we had other cars that got done before yours. Why have a reservation and be told one thing then take in more cars than they can fix so that we have to come back pay for a rental car again. At least 1 time the car still had to come back a 3rd time. We have owned 4 Honda's, 2 BMW's, 2 Toyota's  and have never been treated as rude as Pacific Honda's service dept. does to it's customers. I've watched more customers than I can count on 1 hand be so frustrated they were screaming at the cashier or service advisors when picking up their cars. The response from the Honda reps., is like "Oh well" next customer... We urge you to think about where your hard earned cash is going to go and spend it with another dealership that earns your business. We've all heard this "they got your money now and your screwed" don't let that be you.< /review><rating>2<//rating><date>1430244819246</date>< response>

<rate>5</rate>< Review>
On January 31 we purchased a new 2018 Honda Civic EX from Pacific Honda. And we have Yvon Serov to thank for that. We were searching for a ‚Äúnew" car for my daughter who was looking to replace her 2003 Honda Civic. Initially my daughter planned to purchase a previously owned vehicle because that would fit better into her current financial situation. In addition to Honda Civics and Accords, we also researched Toyota Corollas and Camrys, Mazda 3s, Hyundai Elantras, Subaru Imprezas, Chevy Cruzes, plus Ford Focuses and Fusions.  After all that research, we determined that a Honda Civic was the best in class for the vehicles that my daughter was interested in and could best afford. Thus, we first met Yvon because of my daughter's interest in a 2016 Honda Civic EX that Pacific Honda was offering for sale.

My daughter was able to successfully communicate with Yvon independently of myself and I believe that when Yvon learned that my daughter was also researching new 2018 Honda Civics, he and she began discussing what Pacific Honda could do to compete with other Honda dealerships' best offers. Truthfully I felt somewhat of an obligation with the staff who had been very kind and patient with us taking time and negotiating the best deal to date. So if the offers had been comparable, I would have felt that the other dealership deserved our business. However, when Yvon informed us that Pacific Honda was able to offer an even better price by a few hundred dollars, we were happy to listen.

Again, I was very impressed by the care and respect that Yvon showed my daughter in discussing (via text and phone calls) both previously owned and new Hondas. When the three of us met together, my daughter and I found Yvon to be honest with us and not try to up sell us. He realized that our decision on purchasing a 2018 Honda Civic EX would be fully determined by the best offer. And Yvon made us an offer we could not refuse.

It did not hurt that our family has a long history with Pacific Honda having purchased four vehicles from Pacific Honda over the past two decades‚Äîmy 2000 Odyssey which I am still driving happily, my daughter‚Äôs previously mentioned 2003 Honda Civic, plus the 2006 Honda Accord that one of my sons drives and the 2018 Civic that my other son drives. Plus I have appreciated the fine quality service received from Shawn Dvergsten who has managed the servicing of my Odyssey for many years.

After the purchase, Yvon took his time in explaining the navigation and other parts of the 2018 Civic to my daughter after he had her car cleaned and washed. Yvon was wonderful to work with and I will definitely recommend him to any friends who let me know that they are in the market for a ‚Äúnew‚Äù car. Thank you for having such good staff (both in sales and service) who care about and appreciate your customers.<//Review>

Thank you!'}</response><pictures>None</pictures><Review>What ever happened to customer service? Let me make sure when you read this review you will understand why I'm frustrated and disappointed. The whole experience could have been fantastic review. Here's why...
My Partner and I bought a 2012 Honda Civic LX brand new. Upon getting financed we already knew our finance rate was going to be higher than previously purchased Honda's from the same dealership because of some financial setbacks from 2 years prior. He had to get a car for work reasons and we didn't want some other used car with problems from a previous owner. So the sales person gave us a 17% interest rate which was not negotiable. Again it is what it is. It didn't matter we had bought 2 other brand new Honda's from Pacific Honda. They put my name as the buyer his name as the co-maker. We caught that and that was supposed to have been changed. We got every excuse from it was the bank who did that to they lost the paperwork and so on. Finally after 8 months it appears the names are corrected. He is the legal owner and I the co-signer. Now normally a co-signer does not get monthly bills unless there is a problem with the owner. Up until the last 4-6 months I have received a monthly bill and he sometimes never got one.
He has been paying 17% interest and still is and the dealership has gotten a kick back from Chase Bank for bringing us the customer to them. The amount that gets applied to the principle each month ranges from $175-$200. Our car payment is $423.00 per month. The bank and the dealership are getting more than $225 per month in interest. Now we've all heard of being ripped off but this is what I call getting the screws put to you with a smile. Any reputable business that is truly into customer service and would like a customer to be happy wouldn't do this. We knew the interest was going to be higher before going the Honda dealership but not that high. Pacific Honda is not a buy here pay here tiny dealership or car lot, they are one of the biggest Honda dealerships on the West Coast part of another parent company even larger.
So I would be very careful about buying your next car from this dealership. There has been many times we had little to eat because of struggling to pay them and all the other bills that you have in life.
The service department never answers their phone it's all voicemail. You sit on hold and then get transferred to reservations just to book service. The service advisors will not call you back and more than not the items needed fixed on the car are never done the same day because they need more time. Now remember he dropped his car off at 8-9am they have it all day, he gets a rental pays for the rental and then at 6pm comes back thinking the repairs are going to be done and they aren't. They tell you when you leave the car that they will have everything repaired when you leave it, then it's we got too busy and we had other cars that got done before yours. Why have a reservation and be told one thing then take in more cars than they can fix so that we have to come back pay for a rental car again. At least 1 time the car still had to come back a 3rd time. We have owned 4 Honda's, 2 BMW's, 2 Toyota's  and have never been treated as rude as Pacific Honda's service dept. does to it's customers. I've watched more customers than I can count on 1 hand be so frustrated they were screaming at the cashier or service advisors when picking up their cars. The response from the Honda reps., is like "Oh well" next customer... We urge you to think about where your hard earned cash is going to go and spend it with another dealership that earns your business. We've all heard this "they got your money now and your screwed" don't let that be you.< /Review>< rate>

< Review>
My recent experience with Pacific Honda was exceptional.  For real.

First off, I had done quite a bit of independent research in advance.  This involved discussions with industry-knowledgeable friends, family and co-workers - plus poring over YouTube videos and articles/research/opinions of strangers on the internet.  All of this preliminary groundwork led me to leaning very heavily toward a 2017 Honda Civic.  However, there were about five different options - each quite distinguishable from the others.  And because it is best for one to gather information in order to make an informed decision - it was clear that some further investigating along the front lines had to be done.

Thus, "armed" with my "independent research," I set out for the dealerships.

Not long into that first day of groundwork at the dealerships, my Sales Consultant at Pacific Honda turned out to be Jimmy Gardemann.  That would prove to be quite the lucky break right there.

And because though my research had me "pre-sold" on a Honda (and almost certainly a 2017 Civic), I had not then yet made up my mind on what pro/con blend of features and accessories that I would ultimately opt for.   And in all of these analyses, every positive aspect of a vehicle is counter-balanced to some degree or another by cost/price considerations.

Well, Jimmy really helped out with all that --- as he patiently, candidly and knowledgeably fielded all of my questions (and there were a lot of them).  In other instances, in a no pressure very relaxed manner - he would articulate the various pros, cons and relevant considerations. All of this here was key.  And as Jimmy can also attest, I took copious notes throughout this process - as this was a major decision not to be taken lightly.

All of these visits to the dealers took a full Saturday and Sunday (from open to close each day).  And over that span, I tried pretty much every Honda dealer in San Diego County - all in furtherance of the singular purpose of getting the car I wanted at the best price.  As I continued to negotiate for the best deal, I paid visits to a few of the dealerships more than once.

Long story short:  I got a truly fantastic deal at Pacific Honda (that was unmatchable by the nearest competitors).  Additionally, Jimmy has been absolutely wonderful since our first point of contact on the morning of the 24th right on through to the present day.  In fact, this "post-purchase" level of customer service struck me as particularly remarkable - and further inspired me to write up a review to share my thoughts on Jimmy Gardemann.

Some salespeople have a tendency to pretend to be nice - but Jimmy is the genuine article, the "real McCoy" so to speak.  He's just a legit nice guy that happens to be a straight shooter that is easy to talk to - and one who can shed a lot of light on matters acutely relevant to the Honda car-buying experience.

Summing up the final scorecard:  I landed an awesome car at an unbeatable price with remarkably strong customer service.  More specifically, I hooked a 2017 Honda Civic Hatchback Sport Touring at what I personally verified to be the best price in San Diego - and the customer service at Pacific Honda gets an A+++, from Jimmy to "Sam" (Samantha H.) to Steve and J.R.

And if anyone is looking for a fair, honest and likable car salesperson - with which to discuss the purchase of a Honda (awesome cars by the way), I would urge them to specifically ask for Jimmy Gardemann at Pacific Honda.  [And then feel free to negotiate the heck out of the price - because everybody wants to arrive at a deal that they feel really good about.]<//Review>

< text>
I purchased a car from Pacific Honda and decided to cancel my gap coverage on February 24th 2021. I was first told that it would take around one month to be reimbursed.  After 6 weeks, I called to check on the reimbursement status for multiple days, leaving multiple messages for Richard from finance. I then had to go into their office on my day off because no one would contact me back. Richard then told me that it would be roughly two months from when it was canceled. He also told me he would send me a new confirmation that my coverage has been canceled and I still have not received it. For the past few days I have been reaching out to their finance department and no one has returned any of my calls. It has now been 15 weeks since I canceled the reimbursement and I do not know when I will get it. One bright spot is Gina has been very kind and patient at reception. Unfortunately I have only come across unprofessionalism and a complete lack of customer support from the finance department. If anyone is considering purchasing additionally polices from Pacific Honda when purchasing your car, DO NOT, if you decide to cancel, Pacific Honda will not handle your reimbursement in a remotely professional or timely manor.<//text>
